text:
Heard melodies are sweet, yet those unheard
Are sweeter still; so, gentle pipes, breathe on;
Not to the fleshly ear, but, more endeared,
Sing to the soul your ditties without tone:
Fair youth, beneath the boughs, thou canst not cease
Thy lay, nor ever shall those trees be bare;
Bold lover, never, never canst thou win
That kiss, though near the prize—yet do not care;
She cannot fade, though thou dost lack thy bliss,
For ever shalt thou love, and she be fair!

source_text:
Heard melodies are sweet, but those unheard
Are sweeter; therefore, ye soft pipes, play on;
Not to the sensual ear, but, more endear'd,
Pipe to the spirit ditties of no tone:
Fair youth, beneath the trees, thou canst not leave
Thy song, nor ever can those trees be bare;
Bold Lover, never, never canst thou kiss,
Though winning near the goal--yet, do not grieve;
She cannot fade, though thou hast not thy bliss,
For ever wilt thou love, and she be fair!

